          "body": "Verses 9-11 are among the most concentrated imprecatory prayers in the Psalter, and they have generated significant interpretive debate. The key to reading them correctly is their theological location. They follow the petition 'do not promote his evil device, that they not be exalted' (v. 8), which makes clear that the concern is not David's personal satisfaction but the prevention of wickedness from flourishing in the earth. The imprecations then ask God to enact the covenant curses that Deuteronomy 27-28 had promised against those who perpetrate injustice and violence. 'May the mischief of their lips cover them' (v. 9) is lex talionis — the punishment proportionate to the crime, enacted by the covenant judge. 'May burning coals fall upon them' (v. 10) echoes the destruction of Sodom (Genesis 19:24) and the Psalter's own imagery of divine wrath (Psalm 11:6). The 'deep pits from which they cannot rise' (v. 10) are the pit of Sheol — irreversible divine judgment. Crucially, these are all jussive prayers addressed to God, not declarations of David's own intent. He is handing the judgment to God rather than taking it into his own hands — which is precisely what Romans 12:19 will demand of New Testament believers: 'Vengeance is Mine, I will repay, says the Lord.' The imprecations are, paradoxically, a form of restraint: the believer who prays them is choosing not to act, placing justice in the hands of the only One competent to administer it."
