          "title": "The pivot to certainty — 'I know that the Lord will maintain'",
          "body": "Verse 12 is the psalm's resolution and its most surprising move. After thirteen verses of petition, imprecation, and crisis-language, the psalm ends not with more prayer but with settled declarative confidence: 'I know that the Lord will maintain the cause of the afflicted and justice for the poor.' The verb yada (I know) is the Hebrew word for experiential, relational, covenantal knowledge — the same word used of Adam knowing Eve, and of Israel knowing their God by the Exodus. David does not say 'I hope' or 'I trust'; he says 'I know.' The basis for this knowledge is the character of God as covenant-keeper. The terms 'afflicted' (ani) and 'poor' (evyon) are the Psalter's technical vocabulary for the righteous sufferer who has been stripped of earthly recourse and cast entirely on Yahweh. By adopting this vocabulary for himself in the psalm's closing, David reveals how he understands his own situation: not as a powerful king demanding his rights, but as the archetypally weak one whose only resource is Yahweh's justice. This is the same posture that the Beatitudes will later declare blessed: 'Blessed are the poor in spirit, for theirs is the kingdom of heaven' (Matthew 5:3)."
