          "title": "The final vision — presence, not merely protection",
          "body": "The psalm ends not with safety from enemies but with something greater: 'The upright will dwell in Your presence' (v. 13). The Hebrew paneh (presence, face) is the most intimate word the Old Testament has for access to God — the face-to-face meeting that Moses experienced (Exodus 33:11) and that the Aaronic benediction promised (Numbers 6:25-26). The psalm's final promise is not that the enemy will be punished (though that was the content of vv. 9-11) but that the righteous will be with God. This eschatological vision reorients the entire psalm. The petition for rescue (v. 1) and the imprecation against enemies (vv. 9-11) both serve this end: the removal of wickedness clears the ground for the covenant community's dwelling in God's presence. Tim Keller notes that the lament psalms consistently end not in solutions but in the Presence — which is a greater resolution than solutions could provide. Psalm 140 moves from 'rescue me from evil men' to 'the upright will dwell in Your presence' — and the second is not merely the consequence of the first but the ultimate answer to it. The believer who is hemmed in by enemies on the wayside finds his final geography to be not the road but the face of God."
