        "body": "The opening movement of the psalm is, unexpectedly, not prayer but portrait. David spends five verses constructing an extraordinarily precise description of his enemies before he makes any petition beyond the initial 'rescue me.' This structural choice is theologically significant: honest prayer begins with honest diagnosis. The psalmist who rushes into petition without attending to the actual character and methods of the evil he faces will pray vaguely and be comforted superficially.\n\nThe enemies are described in three concentric registers. First, their character: 'evil men' and 'violent men' (vv. 1, 4) — ra (moral evil) and chamas (violence). Chamas is the word Genesis uses to describe the pre-flood world: 'the earth was filled with violence' (Genesis 6:11). It is not hot-headed aggression but systematic, structural wrongdoing enacted with force. Second, their inner life: they 'devise evil things in their hearts' (v. 2) and 'purposed to trip up my feet' (v. 4). The planning is internal and intentional — chashav (to scheme, to reckon) carries the weight of deliberate craft, not impulse. Third, their methods: a serpent-sharp tongue and viper's venom (v. 3), and the elaborate hunting equipment of verse 5 — trap (pach), cords (chevel), net (reshet), and snares (moqesh), all deployed 'by the wayside.'\n\nThe serpent imagery of verse 3 carries enormous theological weight. In the canonical context of Genesis 3, the serpent's weapon is the tongue — deception deployed through words. The serpent does not bite first; it speaks. David's enemies have mastered the same weaponry. Their verbal violence — slander, false accusation, public defamation — is as lethal as physical assault in a social world where reputation before the king determined survival. The New Testament's own catalogue of verbal evil in Romans 3:13 quotes Psalm 140:3 directly in its diagnosis of universal human depravity: 'Their throat is an open grave, with their tongues they keep deceiving, the poison of asps is under their lips.'\n\nThe proud (geeh, v. 5) who lay traps are driven by the same root sin that animates all wickedness in the Psalter: self-exaltation. Their schemes serve their ambition; their violence is the instrument of their pride. This is why David later prays 'that they not be exalted' (v. 8) — the frustration of their plans is the frustration of their pride.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chamas* (violence) appears three times (vv. 1, 4, 11) — framing the whole psalm with the same word, tying the opening petition to the closing judgment. *Chashav* (devise/scheme, vv. 2, 4) is the craftsman's word — to plan with skill and intentionality. *Pach, reshet, moqesh* are three distinct pieces of hunting equipment piled together in v. 5 to communicate encirclement with no exit."
