        "body": "The pivot into direct address at verse 6 is the psalm's theological hinge. David does not move from threat-description to petition without first establishing the relationship on which every petition rests: 'You are my God.' The verb 'I said' (amar in the Hebrew perfect) likely indicates a deliberate, volitional prior declaration — a formal assertion of covenantal allegiance made in the face of danger. This is not discovering God in a crisis but bringing to the crisis a relationship already consciously affirmed. The possessive 'my' carries all the weight of the Sinai covenant: David is not addressing a generic divine power but the God who has bound Himself by oath to His people and, in this case, by specific promise to His anointed king (2 Samuel 7:8-16).\n\nVerse 6 then makes the first request: 'Give ear, O Lord, to the voice of my supplications.' The Hebrew tachanun (supplications) is the plural of tachanah — earnest petitions made from a position of dependence, not demand. The psalmist asks God to hear not merely the content of the prayer but 'the voice' of it — the quality of urgent, dependent crying. This is similar to Psalm 130:2: 'May Your ears be attentive to the voice of my supplication.'\n\nVerse 7 deepens the theological grounding by moving from present declaration to past memory. 'O God the Lord, the strength of my salvation, You have covered my head in the day of battle.' The accumulation of divine titles — yehovih (the emphatic form of the covenant name), adonai (Lord, sovereign), oz yeshuah (strength of salvation) — is deliberate intensity. In the moment of maximum danger, David reaches for every facet of God's self-disclosed character. Howard Hendricks observed that the Psalms teach us how to pray by teaching us how to address the God to whom we pray. Here David models: when enemies surround you, pile up the names of God — not as magical incantation but as a deliberate act of re-orientation toward Who He is.\n\nThe past-tense memory ('You have covered my head in the day of battle') is the warrant for every present petition. Remembered salvation is the spine of persevering prayer. The same logic appears in Psalm 22:4-5 ('Our fathers cried to You and were delivered'), in Lamentations 3:21-23 ('This I recall to my mind, therefore I have hope'), and in Paul's logic in Romans 5:8 ('While we were yet sinners, Christ died for us' — the past act of God is the ground of present confidence in His love).\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Tachanun* (supplications) is plural — multiple earnest entreaties, not a single request. *Sukh* (covered, shielded, v. 7) is the word for the booth or shelter that provides protection; it is cognate with the word for the Feast of Booths (Sukkot) — God as portable dwelling-place of protection. *Yeshuah* (salvation) shares its root with the name Yeshua — Jesus — making verse 7 a linguistic hinge point for Christological reading."
