        "excerpt": "I know that the Lord will maintain the cause of the afflicted and justice for the poor.",
        "body": "The final two verses of Psalm 140 execute the most dramatic tonal shift in the psalm. After twelve verses of petition, threat-description, and imprecation, the psalm ends not in more prayer but in settled declarative certainty. The shift is marked by 'I know' — yada, the Hebrew word for experiential, covenantal knowing. This is not intellectual assertion but relational conviction grounded in covenant history. David has seen God act; he knows how God acts; therefore he knows what God will do. The present petition stands on this bedrock.\n\nThe content of the certainty is precisely calibrated to the psalm's earlier self-description. In verse 12, David identifies himself implicitly with 'the afflicted' (ani) and 'the poor' (evyon) — the standard Psalter terms for the righteous sufferer who has been stripped of earthly resources and thrown entirely on Yahweh's justice. These are not economic categories alone; they are theological ones. The ani/evyon vocabulary throughout Psalms 9, 10, 22, 34, 35, 37, and 72 describes the one whose only advocate is God. David the king, surrounded by plotting enemies, adopts the posture of the most vulnerable member of the covenant community — because that is, in fact, the posture of every human being before the scheming power of evil. The afflicted and poor are those who have stopped trusting in their own resources and cast themselves entirely on covenant justice.\n\nThe certainty extends in verse 13 to an eschatological vision: 'Surely the righteous will give thanks to Your name; the upright will dwell in Your presence.' The word 'surely' (akh) is an adverb of strong affirmation — not tentative hope but covenant certainty. The final destination of the righteous is not safety from enemies (though that was the petition) but dwelling in God's presence — paneh, the face of God. The same vision closes Psalm 23 ('I will dwell in the house of the LORD forever'), Psalm 17:15 ('I will behold Your face in righteousness; I will be satisfied'), and the entire Psalter's trajectory toward Psalms 146-150. It is ultimately the vision of Revelation 22:4: 'They will see His face.' The psalm that began in crisis ends in the most intimate possible proximity to God.\n\nFor the New Testament reader, verses 12-13 carry explicit Christological force. Jesus, who identified Himself with 'the poor in spirit' in Matthew 5:3 and declared that the kingdom belongs to them, and who quotes the Psalter's afflicted-righteous language in His own passion prayers (Psalm 22 from the cross), is the ultimate fulfillment of the ani/evyon figure. The One whose cause Yahweh maintains is the same One through whom the righteous now dwell in the divine presence. The Davidic psalmist's certainty is the seedbed for the New Testament's assurance that God 'will bring about justice for His elect who cry to Him day and night' (Luke 18:7).\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yada* (I know, v. 12) — experiential, covenantal knowing, not merely intellectual assent. *Ani* (afflicted, oppressed, poor) and *evyon* (destitute, needy) are the Psalter's technical vocabulary for the righteous sufferer who has no human recourse. *Paneh* (presence, face, v. 13) — the most intimate Hebrew word for access to God; the same word used in the Aaronic blessing (Numbers 6:25) and of Moses speaking face-to-face with God (Exodus 33:11). *Akh* (surely) — a strong affirmation particle, introducing the psalm's final unqualified certainty."
